A case study of a green wall system comprising topologically interlocked identical blocks is developed, enabling it to function as a decorative and shaded wall system. A vertical greening system is proposed to reduce carbon emissions and improve competitive advantage. A peripheral frame restraint system is the main structural component. In most cases, the perimeter frame requires special treatment to prevent lateral movement and provide structural support at the boundaries. A similar, perhaps more general type of restraint could also be used in further research to reinforce the structure by utilizing internally pre-tensioned cables. However, the basic component can still be reused. The rest of the structure does not require connectors or adhesives. Two rectangles of the same area but with different directions are used as the basic component and stacked vertically to interpenetrate one another, as shown in Fig. 2
                        a. When the upper and lower elements are stacked, they will provide a mutual binding force. External tensioning cables can further strengthen the simplest constraint. Fig. 2b illustrates the possible constraints while the surrounding structure acts as the frame. Some types of components can be combined (Fig. 3
                        ) to create new models and rules, facilitating the development of more diverse architectural models.
